Optical properties of N, P doped CQDs were investigated using UV–Vis and fluorescence spectrophotometers. The UV–Vis spectrum shows one peak at 346 nm (Fig. 8
                           (a)), this absorption is originated from the trapping of excited state energy by the surface states [59]. The aqueous CQDs solution with a low concentration (18 μL/mL) was illuminated under UV light (312 nm), shown a bright blue colour emission with high intensity (Fig. 8(1&2)). This observation confirmed the high fluorescence emission of synthesized CQDs.The emission spectrum of CQDs at various excitation wavelengths (Fig. 8(b)) confirms the emission is purely based on excitation wavelength. The maximum emission intensity observed at 350 nm with an emission peak of 441 nm (Fig. 8c),this excitation dependent behaviour might be due to the various sizes of particles and distribution of surface states [60], which is in well match with the TEM results (Fig. 8 inset figure). To further evaluate the influence of ethylenediamine and urea phosphate on fluorescence intensity of CQDs, control sample fluorescence intensity was recorded at 350 nm excitations without dilution, which displayed a low emission intensity spectrum (<135) at 441 nm (Fig. S1). This observation indicates that the ethylenediamine and urea phosphate are playing an important role in enhancing the luminescence properties of CQDs. Interestingly, the synthesized CQDs exhibited QY about44.2% and this photoluminescent property is better than the previously reported literature (Table 1
                           ). This result illustrating the robust quantum confinement of N, P doped CQDs which is highly favourable as an extremely sensitive material for chemo-sensors.

The influence of pH on fluorescence intensities of CQDs and CQDs-DA probes were investigated from pH 2–8 (Fig. 13
                           ). CQDs exhibited lower fluorescence intensities at lower pH conditions and intensity was further raised with increasing pH from 5 to 8 pH, no significant changes in fluorescence intensity of CQDs. The reason behind this phenomenon might be due to the protonation of amine moieties results in formation of ammonium salts (NH3
                           +) at lower pH conditions and also the amino group passivation might be another reason for this. Besides, the carboxyl group presence also may influence the intensity of CQDs, the carboxyl group also may get protonated at lower pH conditions, results in aggregation of CQDs, followed by fluorescence quenching [76]. Additionally, the presence of amine and carboxyl groups on the surface of CQDs may promote the hydrophilic properties, dispersibility and stability in water. This observation illustrating that the synthesized CQDs fluorescence intensities are sensitive to lower acidic conditions and almost stable at mild acidic to basic conditions. Even after addition of DA the same pattern is observed. With increasing pH, the fluorescence intensity also increased, but under alkaline condition at pH 8, the fluorescence intensity had declined, it might be due to the additional favourable conditions (pH -8) for further oxidation of DA to dopamine-quinone [74]. Hence, CQDS are stable at mild acidic, neutral and basic conditions and CQDs-DA are stable at mild acidic and neutral conditions.

Fig. 15
 shows the sensitivity of CQDs in presence of DA. The raise in concentration of dopamine from 10 to 500 μM results in gradual quench in the fluorescence intensity of CQDs and a good linear relationship was established between the concentration of DA and F/F0 (R2 = 0.994). The synthesized CQDs achieved the tremendous detection limits compared with the reported literature (Table 2
). The detection limit of CQDs against DA is 0.0218 μM, which was attained at a signal-to-noise ratio of 3. Low LOD and % RSD values indicates that the proposed method has high sensitivity and good reproducibility, results in high feasibility of DA detection in real sample analysis [77].
